<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-445-006  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 445 006.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Simulation  July 1989 v53 n1 p10(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Simulation of a flexible arm robot for space station applications.andO;(Innovative Research program for NASA) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Janssen, Paul J.; Harrand, Vincent J.; Wessling, Francis C.;andO;Choudry, Amar.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A Flexible Arm Robot (FAR), which could be attached to the SpaceStation, could be used for reaching many locations in the vicinityof the Space Station without the need for astronauts in spacesuits to perform extravehicular activity.andP;  FAR is a tube-shapedrobot consisting of many stacked segments which are individuallycontrollable.andP;  Each segment has six degrees of freedom.andP;  Becausethis robot has many degrees of freedom, new algorithms were neededto control it.andP;  A graphical model and a mathematical model (directand inverse kinematics) of FAR have been developed.andP;  Based onthese two models, a software package for simulating this FlexibleArm Robot on a computer system has been made.andP;  FAR and the twomodels are briefly described in this paper.andP;  (Reprinted bypermission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Wyle Laboratories (innovations)Pace and Waite Inc. (innovations).andO;Ticker:    WYL.andO;Topic:     Space ExplorationSimulationRobot ArmsModelingComputer GraphicsAlabama, University of (Huntsville).andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>